<div id="review_3684926098" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3684926098" />
    <a title="Dave Schaafsma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/269235-dave-schaafsma"><img alt="Dave Schaafsma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610298533p2/269235.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3684926098?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dave Schaafsma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dave Schaafsma" href="/user/show/269235-dave-schaafsma">Dave Schaafsma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=science">science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/269235-dave-schaafsma?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3684926098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15225988142172152966">I&apos;ve never been a great sleeper. Not an insomniac, no sleep disorders, but I have always been secretly proud that I &quot;need less sleep than most normal people,&quot; never sleeping as much as any friend or family member. Hey, I&apos;m ambitious, relatively healthy, I like to stay up late and wake early, bam, waking up without the need for coffee, a bit of a lifer adhd kind of guy. But in the last couple years I have begun to listen to doctors about my blood pressure, heart rate, cholestoral, the need to exe</span>
  <span id="freeText15225988142172152966" style="display:none">I've never been a great sleeper. Not an insomniac, no sleep disorders, but I have always been secretly proud that I "need less sleep than most normal people," never sleeping as much as any friend or family member. Hey, I'm ambitious, relatively healthy, I like to stay up late and wake early, bam, waking up without the need for coffee, a bit of a lifer adhd kind of guy. But in the last couple years I have begun to listen to doctors about my blood pressure, heart rate, cholestoral, the need to exercise and lose weight, and especially this year have begun to take it all seriously. <br /><br />And I have been reading a bit about the important role of sleep in mental and physical health, so in many ways this book did not surprise me in any way. Research reveals strong correlations between sleep and serious disease in the US and other western, industrialized countries. It's a sign of commitment, and alpha-ness to sleep less. The leaders sleep little in any profession, we seem to know. But this book reminds me that Alzheimer's, cancer, diabetes, the high suicide rate, relationship problems, and so much more has to do with sleep deprivation.<br /><br />Guilty, except in the past year when I have begun to make a commitment to figuring out how to sleep more, and (especially) get more REM sleep. I'm a light sleeper. Drink less, especially later at night, meditate, exercise... I'm still not up to an average of 7 hours a night, and may never consistently get there, but I'm convinced it is better for me. I knew sleep was important for child development, but now I am sure it is better for me, too, as I age.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15225988142172152966" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


